===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|smilen||to smile|lang=enm}}, of {{etyl|gmq|en}} origin, from {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|smile||to smile|lang=da}}, from {{etyl|non|-}} *{{term||smīla|to smile|lang=non}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|smīlijaną|lang=gem-pro}}, {{recons|smirōną||to smile|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|(s)meyə-||to laugh, be glad, wonder|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|smila||to smile|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|smielen||to smile|lang=gmh}}, {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|smieron|smierōn|to smile|lang=goh}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|smerian||to laugh at|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|smercian|lang=ang}}, {{term|smearcian||to smile|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|miror||to wonder at|lang=la}}. More at {{l|en|smirk}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A facial [[expression]] comprised by [[flex]]ing the [[muscle]]s of both ends of one's [[mouth]] while showing the front [[tooth|teeth]], without [[vocalisation]], and in humans is a common involuntary or voluntary expression of [[happiness]], [[pleasure]], [[amusement]] or [[anxiety]].
#: ''She's got a perfect '''smile'''.''
#: ''He has a sinister '''smile'''.''
#: ''She had a '''smile''' on her face.''
#: ''He always puts a '''smile''' on my face.''

